From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date: Fri, 19 Jun 2026 17:52:08 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] uu_cat: add injected-I/O logical entry for an in-process
 brush builtin

Adapt the vendored uu_cat so it can run as an in-process brush builtin
that reads/writes the shell's logical OpenFile sink and source instead of
the process's global stdin/stdout. New public entry point:

    pub fn cat(args, out: &mut dyn Write, out_fd: Option<BorrowedFd>,
               stdin: &mut dyn Read, stdin_fd: Option<BorrowedFd>)

out/stdin are the logical streams; out_fd/stdin_fd are their backing
descriptors when one exists (None for an in-memory stream). The Linux
splice(2) fast path is kept and gated on both ends having a real fd; an
fd-less end takes the copy loop. write_fast flushes out before splicing
so a buffered, fd-backed sink (e.g. line-buffered stdout) can't have its
buffered bytes reordered behind the spliced bytes.

To support fd-less inputs, the FdReadable (Read + AsFd) bound and the
generic InputHandle<R> are replaced by a non-generic InputHandle holding
&mut dyn Read + Option<RawFd>; splice.rs takes two BorrowedFd instead of
the handle. The self-overwrite guard (is_unsafe_overwrite) now fires only
when both fds exist.

uumain is retained as a thin descriptor-based bridge over cat() for the
standalone binary and the --invoke-bundled subprocess dispatcher, where
the process's own fd 0/1 are the intended I/O. The engine consumes the
vendored copy via [patch.crates-io].

Verified: builds on the static musl target (make engine); the patched
crate compiles warning-free and its splice fast path is exercised under
strace for in-memory, file, pipe, and buffered-fd sinks.

